post_text: Frontier released its re-opening plan on July 21. We are offering parents a choice that works best for their family. Parents can choose in‐person attendance or virtual learning. Since the release of our re-opening plan, COVID-19 remains a great concern in the Kansas City area. Because of this, and in response to the increasing number of cases in the metro area, our re-opening committee has decided to move the start date for all students to August 31. Frontier will provide virtual instruction to all students between August 31 and September 18. During this time period, we will continue to monitor the conditions and guidance from the CDC and local health departments. Based on their guidance and feedback, we may start providing in-person instruction to the students who chose this option beginning on September 21.
text: Frontier released its re-opening plan on July 21. We are offering parents a choice that works best for their family. Parents can choose in‐person attendance or virtual learning. Since the release of our re-opening plan, COVID-19 remains a great concern in the Kansas City area. Because of this, and in response to the increasing number of cases in the metro area, our re-opening committee has decided to move the start date for all students to August 31. Frontier will provide virtual instruction to all students between August 31 and September 18. During this time period, we will continue to monitor the conditions and guidance from the CDC and local health departments. Based on their guidance and feedback, we may start providing in-person instruction to the students who chose this option beginning on September 21.

post_text:
Dear Parents & Guardians,

Frontier Schools has released its re-opening plan for the start of the 2020-21 school year. We are offering parents a choice that works best for their family. Parents can choose in‐person attendance or virtual learning. Soon, you will be getting a call from your school’s front office staff to determine what option is best for your family. For more information, please visit our website – www.frontierschools.org.

Thank you.

post_text:
Dear Parents and Guardians,

Wednesday, June 24th, will be the last day that we will provide grab-and-go meals for the students enrolled in Frontier Schools. Parents and guardians can pick up meals between 11:30 am and 1:30 pm at our North location: Frontier School of Innovation – 1575 Universal Ave., Kansas City, MO 64120 (in front of the gym).

Breakfast and lunch meals will resume in August. More information will be provided in late July.

Thank you.

April 29 at 4:30 PM ·

Wednesday Weekly Shout Out!

Margaret Keeler - Ms. Keeler is successfully teaching Shakespeare's Romeo and Juliet to her 9th graders virtually! She has engaging live classes, assigns rigorous, but meaningful assignments, and has been a great help to FSE staff as they navigate teaching online! She is always looking for new and engaging ways to interact with her students and has had a positive attitude the entire time! #TheBrightSide

post_text:
Dear Frontier Family,

You may have heard the news that Governor Mike Parson has indicated that schools in our state will not reopen this school year. The Governor’s stay-at-home order remains in place as do federal guidelines around social distancing that extend thru April 30.

Frontier Schools’ buildings will remain closed for the rest of the school year. Knowing that our connection with our families is crucial right now, we plan to continue to support our students and school community. This support includes the continuation of virtual instruction, the provision of social-emotional and wellness supports and grab and go meals.

We will inform our staff and students regarding the summer school program when more information is available from DESE.
#TheBrightSide
text:
Dear Frontier Family,

You may have heard the news that Governor Mike Parson has indicated that schools in our state will not reopen this school year. The Governor’s stay-at-home order remains in place as do federal guidelines around social distancing that extend thru April 30.

Frontier Schools’ buildings will remain closed for the rest of the school year. Knowing that our connection with our families is crucial right now, we plan to continue to support our students and school community. This support includes the continuation of virtual instruction, the provision of social-emotional and wellness supports and grab and go meals.

We will inform our staff and students regarding the summer school program when more information is available from DESE.
#TheBrightSide

post_text:
In preparation for a potential school closure following our spring break holiday, we will transition to an alternate instruction method. This alternate method of instruction will ensure that our students are continuing to learn at home. All parents and/or guardians will need to stop by your child's school to pick up a Chromebook, sign a consent form and provide current contact information. Front office hours will be 12:00pm - 5:00pm on Friday, March 13th and 9:00am - 4:00pm on Saturday, March 15th.

If you have any questions or concerns, please contact your school.

shared_text:
SunSource Homes
February 6 at 11:22 PM ·

We stopped by the Frontier School of Excellence career fair today to talk to the kids about careers in solar.
For all but one student it was their first time seeing a solar panel in person + learning how solar works.
Many were shocked about the different solar career paths, like being an engineer or marketer, + now have solar on their radar as a possible career interest.
The general consensus from the attendees was that they weren't sure if they would go into a solar career, but they all surely wanted solar on their future homes + businesses.
☀️Special thanks to our head architect, John, for answering all the kiddo's questions!

Today was the first day back to school after winter break for schools across KC. Frontier Schools held their annual Million Fathers March to welcome kids back to school! Officer Greg Smith, Major Doug Niemeier, and Captain Jeff Hughley with Kansas City Missouri Police Department East Patrol were among the group of men welcoming kids as they hopped off the bus!
